node.text: Swimming for something BIGGER! A 2018 study revealed only 13% of our oceans are considered truly wild, but what's worse is this (scary) statistic has gone relatively unnoticed. Why? Well, partly because the sea (and its inhabitants) require a bigger "voice" to be heard. To quote the great Sir @davidattenborough “This is a communication challenge rather than a scientific one. We need to make it easy for the world to understand the issues and to enable an increasingly urban population to connect with nature and feel a shared responsibility for it.” Which is exactly why last weekend myself and the Talisker team took to the water (equipped with a plentiful supply of bananas) in support of @Talisker and @Parley.TV on their mission to Rewild Our Seas and created this short film (see link in my bio for more information) #TaliskerParley #RewildOurSeas #WildSpirit

node.text: Continuing to share my strategies for coping with isolation based on the teachings of my new book #TheArtOfResilience documenting the 157 days I spent at sea (share and tag someone who needs to hear this) Research published in the Frontiers in Human Neuroscience took a group of athletes and had them cycle to exhaustion. One group were shown subliminal visual cues of happy faces, the other group was shown subliminal visual cues of sad faces. What did they find? That “individuals cycled significantly longer when subliminally primed with happy faces”. They added, “These experiments are the first to show that subliminal visual cues relating to affect and action can alter perception of effort and endurance performance.” BIG thank you (again) to @BritishGQ for asking me to speak at this year’s GQ Heroes last year & @hendogq for being a brilliant interviewer 😃

node.text: Talking about the teachings of my new book #TheArtOfResilience (see link in bio for your copy) I never imagined the lessons learnt from 157 days at sea (staring at the ocean bed for over 1,000 hours left alone with my own thoughts) would become so relevant to helping so many people cope with isolation, adversity and a fear of the unknown. But if you (or anyone you know) can take comfort from the stoic teachings that I used at sea, then I will produce weekly videos on ancient stoic philosophy and strategies to cope with adversity that have been tried and tested over thousands of years. The topic of this first video is to briefly explain the origins of Stoicism and how it can help you identify the: Controllables vs Uncontrollables in your daily life. To quote Epictetus, "The chief task in life is simply this: to identify and separate matters so that I can say clearly to myself which are externals not under my control, and which have to do with the choices I actually control. Where then do I look for good and evil? Not to uncontrollable externals, but within myself to the choices that are my own."

node.text: This year's @talisker Whisky Atlantic Challenge has 103 rowers in 35 teams from 12 countries competing across 3,000 miles of ocean from (La Gomera) Tenerife to Antigua. node.text: (Tag friends who’d appreciate this) Experimenting with a higher proportion of fat in the diet which is why today's session I'm to fuel my longer, low intensity cardio sessions with @TheProteinWorks Salted Caramel Cookie Ocean Loaded Nuts. As per the teachings of #TheArtOfResilience (SEE LINK IN BIO TO PRE ORDER) this isn't because I'm trying to achieve ketosis, but instead because research shows we can’t eat enough carbohydrates and store enough muscle glycogen to fuel ULTRA LONG endurance events. This is why research conducted at Harvard Medical School said, “While the maximum size of the glycogen reservoir available to an endurance runner depends on the size of the relevant muscles, it is possible to estimate the amount of accessible glycogen: A lean, male runner, for example, may be 45% skeletal muscle by mass, with half of that mass in his leg muscles; at 70 kg such an athlete would typically store 310 g of carbohydrate as muscle glycogen, and could store at most approximately 570 g, corresponding to approximately 1250 and 2270 kcal of leg muscle glycogen, respectively.” The study adds, “Considering the total carbohydrate-based energy reserve from muscle glycogen, liver glycogen, and plasma glucose, it becomes clear that normal carbohydrate stores alone would be insufficient to fuel a marathon.” The solution? Add fat. This is because research published in the American Journal of Physiology found working muscles consume a mixture of metabolic substrates, and the relative contributions of fat and carbohydrate to this mixture dynamically depend on exercise intensity and the size of available glycogen reservoirs. It’s concluded, “Carbohydrates account for a greater proportion at higher intensities, while fat accounts for a greater proportion as available glycogen is depleted.” This is because research published by Nutrition Focus New Zealand Limited found, "The number of gruelling events that challenge the limits of human endurance is increasing. But documenting the methodology of my WINTER (BASE) MESOCYCLE with the MASSIVE man hero @eddiehallwsm is 100% a HUGE highlight! To directly quote the book, “The focus is to create an ‘athletic base’ with a high volume of training at a low intensity while also improving work capacity (the body’s ability to perform and positively tolerate training of a given intensity or duration). This is achieved through a system of training called General Physical Preparedness (targeted at strength and endurance) that was pioneered in the old Soviet Union (1922 to 1991), but is done under conditions that take inspiration from the Spartan warrior society of ancient Greece (431-404 B.C) to build mental resilience as well as work capacity” 💪🏽 Tag friends, training partners and anyone who needs this book on their life 🙏

node.text: Good & Bad News 🔱 I wanted to post to ‘shed some light’ on my recent training (since getting lots of questions on the mileage). In short, I was covering 30km a day (for 20 days) for an EPIC idea we had for a swim in the name of science & marine conservation! The good news is scans reveal my shoulder has fully healed & handled that volume of training really well (ALL my rehab & conditioning is in my NEW book #BLUEPRINT: see link in bio). The bad news is covid and lockdown has meant we’re unable to start the project 😞 Obviously as a team we’re disappointed, but we’re equally undeterred and will regroup, replan and reschedule 😊 but I just felt I needed to post since it’s been a few months now of midnight marathons & I wanted to explain why 🙏 Lastly HUGE thank you to @gymshark & @phdnutrition who’ve been INCREDIBLE in supporting the sports science of this venture. But rest assured this is a comma, not a full stop 😉 #PerformSmart #Gymshark

node.text: The countdown begins 🤩 Just weeks before my NEW book the #Blueprint is released (SEE LINK IN BIO) 🔱 This book began as a set of ‘sports science scribbles’ in my training journal as I researched the damage caused by the #GreatBritishSwim and studied ways to speed up my recovery so I could go from the surgery table back to the sea as fast as possible. But along the way it turned into something SO MUCH MORE, which is why I'm hoping it equips every "scholar athlete" (Plato) with a 365-day training plan to condition their body (and mind) for any athletic adventure 💪🏽
